{"title": "Prove I Am Not Bluffing", "content": "When a character deliberately Kicks the Dog or crosses the Moral Event Horizon just to prove a point. Maybe you want to prove that you are willing to make good on a threat, maybe you just want to show that you're not the kind of person they want to mess with. Either way the message is the same: \"I'm willing to do this just to make a point, so imagine what I'd do if you gave me a reason.\" Particularly effective when the character harms something they like (like one of their favorite henchmen), as it shows they will be far less merciful to anything that they don't like.\n\nThis can backfire if taken too far though; it might simply convince your opponent that you are beyond all reason or that you cannot be trusted, and decide that a more decisive and ruthless approach is needed, or maybe you end up looking so Obviously Evil that your otherwise reasonable demands are no longer taken seriously, which often happens when there is a clash between moderates and extremists. On the other hand, maybe that's what you are counting on, and you want the other side to escalate things to make them look bad, extreme and unreasonable. And so on it goes, so this trope can lead to, or be the result of, some complex Gambit Pileups and Serial Escalations.\n\nSee If You're So Evil, Eat This Kitten for when a character is challenged to do this.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ProveIAmNotBluffing", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/Bleach", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VisualNovel/UminekoWhenTheyCry", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Ronin", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Taken", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/BrokenArrow1996", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/JamesBond", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Thunderball", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/AustinPowersTheSpyWhoShaggedMe", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/IndependenceDay", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TrueLies", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/SamuelLJackson", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheNegotiator", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/